May 8, 1998<br>
<br>
Lawyers in Eastern Kentucky are looking for clients who might take part in a possible class-action lawsuit charging that the coal industry has for decades cheated on dust tests, leading thousands of miners to contract black lung.<br>
<br>
Greg Stumbo, a lawyer from Prestonsburg and the state House majority leader, is placing large advertisements in local newspapers stating, &quot;Attention Underground Coal Miners: If you worked in an underground mine and were forced by your employer to falsify dust samples . . . PLEASE CALL GREGORY D. STUMBO . . . (who) is investigating this matter and a potential class action is now forming.&quot;<br>
<br>
Stumbo said he'll begin airing TV ads &quot;just as quick as I can get to Lexington and have one shot.&quot;<br>
<br>
Rep. Herbie Deskins of Pikeville, who is also a lawyer, said he talked about the lawsuit on a local radio program recently, and as a result already has two potential clients.<br>
<br>
Both Stumbo and Deskins say the defendants could include Gov. Paul Patton, a former coal operator who pushed changes in the workers' compensation sustem through the General Assembly in 1996. The changes have made it all but impossible for miners to collect black-lung disability benefits -- and cost both Stumbo and Deskins thousands of dollars a year in legal business.<br>
<br>
In the hallway of Stumbo's law office are piles of bumper stickers with the message, &quot;Flatten Patton.&quot;<br>
<br>
A recent Courier-Journal series, &quot;Dust, Deception and Death,&quot; found that coal operators, with the help of miners, routinely cheat on dust tests. As a result, miners are often forced to breathe dangerous and illegal levels of dust, and hundreds die each year of black lung.<br>
<br>
The newspaper suggested that class-action lawsuits like those filed in recent years against major cigarette manufacturers could force the industry to clean up its mines.<br>
<br>
Stumbo vowed to spend almost all of his time over the next seven months trying to determine whether a class-action lawsuit is feasible against the coal industry. With the help of national experts, he hopes to file such a suit by the end of the year, although he acknowledged that there are huge hurdles to overcome.<br>
